class LUPrefix {
    int[] prefixLengths;
    int n;

    public LUPrefix(int n) {
        this.n = n;
        prefixLengths = new int[n + 1];
        Arrays.fill(prefixLengths, 0);
    }

    public void upload(int video) {
        prefixLengths[video]++;
    }

    public int longest() {
        int maxIndex = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            if (prefixLengths[i] > maxIndex) {
                maxIndex = i;
            }
        }
        return maxIndex;
    }
}
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

We use an array `prefixLengths` to store the length of the longest uploaded prefix for each index. The `upload` method updates the `prefixLengths` array by incrementing the value at the current index `i`. The `longest` method iterates through the `prefixLengths` array from index 1 to `n`, comparing each value with the current maximum (`maxIndex`). If a new maximum is found, we update `maxIndex`. Finally, we return `maxIndex`, which represents the length of the longest uploaded prefix.

The time complexity is O(n) because we iterate through the `prefixLengths` array once. The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a single integer array. The energy implications are low because the algorithm does not require any additional energy consumption beyond the initial setup.

